value.value: A country in central Europe, southeast of Germany and southwest of Poland.

label.value: Recurrent Breast Implant-Associated Anaplastic Large Cell Lymphoma

value.value: The reemergence of breast implant-associated anaplastic large cell lymphoma after a period of remission.

label.value: Refractory Breast Implant-Associated Anaplastic Large Cell Lymphoma

value.value: Breast implant-associated anaplastic large cell lymphoma that is resistant to treatment.

label.value: Locally Recurrent Head and Neck Squamous Cell Carcinoma

value.value: The reemergence of head and neck squamous cell carcinoma after a period of remission, at or adjacent to the site of the original tumor.
A laboratory test result indicating the presence of HLA-A*03:01 positive cells in a tissue sample.

label.value: Measurable Residual Disease Less than 0.1 Percent

value.value: An indication that a biomarker for a neoplastic disease is present in less than 0.1 percent of a sample.

label.value: Neoplastic Plasma Cells 5 Percent or More of Peripheral Blood White Cells

value.value: A semi-quantitative microscopic finding indicating that at least 5 percent of the leukocytes in a peripheral blood sample are neoplastic plasma cells.

label.value: Crosslinked Multimeric Type III Procollagen Propeptide

value.value: Crosslinked complexes comprised of multiple copies of the N-terminal propeptide derived from type III procollagen. Quantitation of the level of these peptides in blood samples may serve as a marker for liver fibrosis or steatosis.

label.value: Ki-67 Positive Cells Greater than or Equal to 5 Percent

value.value: A semi-quantitative microscopic finding indicating that at least 5 percent of the cells in a sample are detected following staining using an anti-Ki-67 antibody.
An indication that SARS coronavirus 2 has not been detected in a sample.
A mutation in an NTRK family gene that results in constitutive activation of the encoded NTRK family receptor protein and downstream pathways.
A country in central Europe, south of Poland and north of Hungary.
One-thousandth of a siemens, a decimal fraction of the SI unit of electrical conductance and admittance siemens and is equal to 10^-3 siemens.

A change in the nucleotide sequence of the MET gene that that results in loss of transcription of MET exon 14 and constitutive activation of hepatocyte growth factor receptor and its downstream signaling pathways.
An immune system finding indicating that an individual has a likelihood for developing Epstein Barr virus infections.
An immune system finding indicating that an individual has a higher than normal tendency to develop bacterial infections.
An immune system finding indicating that an individual has a higher than normal tendency to develop fungal infections.
An immune system finding indicating that an individual has a higher than normal tendency to develop viral infections.
A class of genetic diseases that occur when microsatellite repeats expand beyond a threshold length.
A rare, aggressive, high-grade, and poorly differentiated carcinoma with neuroendocrine differentiation that arises from the rectum. It is characterized by the presence of malignant large cells.
Body temperature of 104 degrees Fahrenheit (40 degrees Celsius) or higher.
Body temperature ranging between 102.1 degrees Fahrenheit (39 degrees Celsius) and 103.9 degrees Fahrenheit (39.9 degrees Celsius).

A quassinoid phytochemical isolated from Simaba cedron and other plant species with potential antineoplastic activity.  Chaparrin is a mixture of compounds that includes flavonoids, antioxidants, and nordihydroguaiaretic acid (NDGA).  NDGA is an antioxidant and lipoxygenase inhibitor that promotes cell differentiation, induces G1 phase cell-cycle arrest, and causes apoptosis in certain cancer cell lines. (NCI04)

Cytoplasmic Receptors are selective binding proteins that mediate the physiologic effects of specific bound regulatory molecules, such as hormones that cause a conformational and functional change in the receptor molecule. Interaction of the ligand-bound receptor with target molecules is altered, which leads to changes in cellular physiology through modification of the activity of one or more signal transduction pathways. Steroid receptors are cytoplasmic carriers that translocate to the nucleus upon ligand binding and regulate the expression of specific target genes.
Beta radiation produced by the decay of phosphorous-32.
Sebaceous epithelioma occurring in a dog.

A condition occurring in cats characterized by solitary or multiple cutaneous nodules and papules, which may metastasize late in the course of the disease. Lesions consist of poorly circumscribed histiocytic infiltrates of the superficial and deep dermis, with variable extension into the subcutis.

An autosomal dominant condition caused by mutation(s) in the PIK3R1 gene, encoding phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase regulatory subunit alpha. It is characterized by a heterogenous phenotype, including recurrent respiratory infections, lymphoproliferation, and antibody deficiency. There is an increased likelihood of development of B-cell lymphoma.

An autosomal recessive condition caused by mutation(s) in the YARS gene encoding tyrosine-tRNA ligase. It is characterized by a variable phenotype which may include poor growth, developmental delay, abnormal brain white matter, hearing loss, involuntary eye movements, progressive cholestatic liver disease, pancreatic insufficiency, hypoglycemia, anemia, intermittent excess of protein in urine, recurrent bloodstream infections, and chronic pulmonary disease.
A lung neuroendocrine tumor that is associated with carcinoid syndrome.
A lung neuroendocrine tumor that is not associated with carcinoid syndrome.

The result of an evaluation of the body and its functions using visual inspection, palpation, percussion, or auscultation that is performed to determine the presence, absence, or degree of a condition.
The result of an evaluation technique using a visual display of structural or functional patterns of organs or tissues that is performed to determine the presence, absence, or degree of a condition.
A sign, symptom, or clinical test result related to the breast.

Proteins that regulate transcription via interaction with chromatin and basal transcription machinery at the promoter regions of genes. Nuclear receptors are ligand-dependent transcription factors including steroids, retinoids, vitamin D, unliganded thyroid hormone, and orphan receptors (unknown ligands). Coregulators (coactivators or corepressors) are important in mediating these interactions and thereby modulate positive or negative receptor activity.
The result of an examination of the breast that is performed by a health care provider to check for lumps or other changes.
The reemergence of a lung neuroendocrine neoplasm after a period of remission.
A symptom that is associated with a cancer diagnosis or its treatment.
Improper use or treatment that is generally considered harmful.
A symptom or problem for which a patient seeks medical attention.
A lung neuroendocrine neoplasm that has spread from its original site of growth to nearby tissues or lymph nodes.
The result of an evaluation of an individual's ability to endure the workload that is achieved during a specified period of exercise.
A loss of structural integrity within a tissue or organ.
The functional state of the body or body systems.
A sign, symptom, or clinical test result related to the lymph nodes.

A technique in crystallography in which the pattern produced by the diffraction of x-rays through the closely spaced lattice of atoms in a crystal is recorded and then analyzed to reveal the nature of that lattice.
The state of a drug product in relation to the patient or study subject for whom it is prescribed or assigned.
The patient has not met the specified clinical criteria for the diagnosis of interest.
The patient has met the specified clinical criteria for the diagnosis of interest.
